{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"If you ask people about what part of psychology do they think is hard,"},{"time":6000,"text":"and you say, \"Well, what about thinking and emotions?\""},{"time":9000,"text":"Most people will say, \"Emotions are terribly hard."},{"time":12000,"text":"They're incredibly complex. They can't -- I have no idea of how they work."},{"time":18000,"text":"But thinking is really very straightforward:"},{"time":20000,"text":"it's just sort of some kind of logical reasoning, or something."},{"time":24000,"text":"But that's not the hard part.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":27000,"text":"So here's a list of problems that come up."},{"time":29000,"text":"One nice problem is, what do we do about health?"},{"time":32000,"text":"The other day, I was reading something, and the person said"},{"time":36000,"text":"probably the largest single cause of disease is handshaking in the West."},{"time":42000,"text":"And there was a little study about people who don't handshake,"},{"time":46000,"text":"and comparing them with ones who do handshake."},{"time":49000,"text":"And I haven't the foggiest idea of where you find the ones that don't handshake,"},{"time":54000,"text":"because they must be hiding."},{"time":57000,"text":"And the people who avoid that"},{"time":61000,"text":"have 30 percent less infectious disease or something."},{"time":65000,"text":"Or maybe it was 31 and a quarter percent."},{"time":68000,"text":"So if you really want to solve the problem of epidemics and so forth,"},{"time":72000,"text":"let's start with that. And since I got that idea,"},{"time":76000,"text":"I've had to shake hundreds of hands."},{"time":80000,"text":"And I think the only way to avoid it"},{"time":85000,"text":"is to have some horrible visible disease,"},{"time":87000,"text":"and then you don't have to explain."}]},{"cues":[{"time":90000,"text":"Education: how do we improve education?"},{"time":94000,"text":"Well, the single best way is to get them to understand"},{"time":98000,"text":"that what they're being told is a whole lot of nonsense."},{"time":101000,"text":"And then, of course, you have to do something"},{"time":103000,"text":"about how to moderate that, so that anybody can -- so they'll listen to you."},{"time":108000,"text":"Pollution, energy shortage, environmental diversity, poverty."},{"time":112000,"text":"How do we make stable societies? Longevity."},{"time":116000,"text":"Okay, there're lots of problems to worry about."}]},{"cues":[{"time":119000,"text":"Anyway, the question I think people should talk about --"},{"time":121000,"text":"and it's absolutely taboo -- is, how many people should there be?"},{"time":126000,"text":"And I think it should be about 100 million or maybe 500 million."},{"time":133000,"text":"And then notice that a great many of these problems disappear."},{"time":138000,"text":"If you had 100 million people"},{"time":140000,"text":"properly spread out, then if there's some garbage,"},{"time":146000,"text":"you throw it away, preferably where you can't see it, and it will rot."},{"time":153000,"text":"Or you throw it into the ocean and some fish will benefit from it."},{"time":158000,"text":"The problem is, how many people should there be?"},{"time":160000,"text":"And it's a sort of choice we have to make."}]},{"cues":[{"time":163000,"text":"Most people are about 60 inches high or more,"},{"time":166000,"text":"and there's these cube laws. So if you make them this big,"},{"time":170000,"text":"by using nanotechnology, I suppose --"},{"time":173000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":174000,"text":"-- then you could have a thousand times as many."},{"time":176000,"text":"That would solve the problem, but I don't see anybody"},{"time":178000,"text":"doing any research on making people smaller."},{"time":181000,"text":"Now, it's nice to reduce the population, but a lot of people want to have children."},{"time":186000,"text":"And there's one solution that's probably only a few years off."},{"time":189000,"text":"You know you have 46 chromosomes. If you're lucky, you've got 23"},{"time":194000,"text":"from each parent. Sometimes you get an extra one or drop one out,"},{"time":200000,"text":"but -- so you can skip the grandparent and great-grandparent stage"},{"time":204000,"text":"and go right to the great-great-grandparent. And you have 46 people"},{"time":209000,"text":"and you give them a scanner, or whatever you need,"},{"time":212000,"text":"and they look at their chromosomes and each of them says"},{"time":216000,"text":"which one he likes best, or she -- no reason to have just two sexes"},{"time":221000,"text":"any more, even. So each child has 46 parents,"},{"time":226000,"text":"and I suppose you could let each group of 46 parents have 15 children."},{"time":232000,"text":"Wouldn't that be enough? And then the children"},{"time":234000,"text":"would get plenty of support, and nurturing, and mentoring,"},{"time":238000,"text":"and the world population would decline very rapidly"},{"time":240000,"text":"and everybody would be totally happy."}]},{"cues":[{"time":243000,"text":"Timesharing is a little further off in the future."},{"time":246000,"text":"And there's this great novel that Arthur Clarke wrote twice,"},{"time":249000,"text":"called \"Against the Fall of Night\" and \"The City and the Stars.\""},{"time":253000,"text":"They're both wonderful and largely the same,"},{"time":256000,"text":"except that computers happened in between."},{"time":258000,"text":"And Arthur was looking at this old book, and he said, \"Well, that was wrong."},{"time":263000,"text":"The future must have some computers.\""},{"time":265000,"text":"So in the second version of it, there are 100 billion"},{"time":270000,"text":"or 1,000 billion people on Earth, but they're all stored on hard disks or floppies,"},{"time":278000,"text":"or whatever they have in the future."},{"time":280000,"text":"And you let a few million of them out at a time."},{"time":284000,"text":"A person comes out, they live for a thousand years"},{"time":288000,"text":"doing whatever they do, and then, when it's time to go back"},{"time":294000,"text":"for a billion years -- or a million, I forget, the numbers don't matter --"},{"time":298000,"text":"but there really aren't very many people on Earth at a time."},{"time":302000,"text":"And you get to think about yourself and your memories,"},{"time":304000,"text":"and before you go back into suspension, you edit your memories"},{"time":309000,"text":"and you change your personality and so forth."},{"time":312000,"text":"The plot of the book is that there's not enough diversity,"},{"time":318000,"text":"so that the people who designed the city"},{"time":321000,"text":"make sure that every now and then an entirely new person is created."},{"time":325000,"text":"And in the novel, a particular one named Alvin is created. And he says,"},{"time":331000,"text":"maybe this isn't the best way, and wrecks the whole system."}]},{"cues":[{"time":335000,"text":"I don't think the solutions that I proposed"},{"time":337000,"text":"are good enough or smart enough."},{"time":340000,"text":"I think the big problem is that we're not smart enough"},{"time":344000,"text":"to understand which of the problems we're facing are good enough."},{"time":348000,"text":"Therefore, we have to build super intelligent machines like HAL."},{"time":352000,"text":"As you remember, at some point in the book for \"2001,\""},{"time":357000,"text":"HAL realizes that the universe is too big, and grand, and profound"},{"time":362000,"text":"for those really stupid astronauts. If you contrast HAL's behavior"},{"time":366000,"text":"with the triviality of the people on the spaceship,"},{"time":370000,"text":"you can see what's written between the lines."},{"time":373000,"text":"Well, what are we going to do about that? We could get smarter."},{"time":376000,"text":"I think that we're pretty smart, as compared to chimpanzees,"},{"time":381000,"text":"but we're not smart enough to deal with the colossal problems that we face,"},{"time":387000,"text":"either in abstract mathematics"},{"time":389000,"text":"or in figuring out economies, or balancing the world around."},{"time":394000,"text":"So one thing we can do is live longer."},{"time":397000,"text":"And nobody knows how hard that is,"},{"time":399000,"text":"but we'll probably find out in a few years."},{"time":402000,"text":"You see, there's two forks in the road. We know that people live"},{"time":405000,"text":"twice as long as chimpanzees almost,"},{"time":409000,"text":"and nobody lives more than 120 years,"},{"time":413000,"text":"for reasons that aren't very well understood."},{"time":416000,"text":"But lots of people now live to 90 or 100,"},{"time":419000,"text":"unless they shake hands too much or something like that."},{"time":423000,"text":"And so maybe if we lived 200 years, we could accumulate enough skills"},{"time":428000,"text":"and knowledge to solve some problems."},{"time":433000,"text":"So that's one way of going about it."},{"time":435000,"text":"And as I said, we don't know how hard that is. It might be --"},{"time":438000,"text":"after all, most other mammals live half as long as the chimpanzee,"},{"time":444000,"text":"so we're sort of three and a half or four times, have four times"},{"time":447000,"text":"the longevity of most mammals. And in the case of the primates,"},{"time":453000,"text":"we have almost the same genes. We only differ from chimpanzees,"},{"time":457000,"text":"in the present state of knowledge, which is absolute hogwash,"},{"time":463000,"text":"maybe by just a few hundred genes."}]},{"cues":[{"time":465000,"text":"What I think is that the gene counters don't know what they're doing yet."},{"time":468000,"text":"And whatever you do, don't read anything about genetics"},{"time":471000,"text":"that's published within your lifetime, or something."},{"time":474000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":477000,"text":"The stuff has a very short half-life, same with brain science."},{"time":481000,"text":"And so it might be that if we just fix four or five genes,"},{"time":487000,"text":"we can live 200 years."},{"time":489000,"text":"Or it might be that it's just 30 or 40,"},{"time":492000,"text":"and I doubt that it's several hundred."},{"time":494000,"text":"So this is something that people will be discussing"},{"time":498000,"text":"and lots of ethicists -- you know, an ethicist is somebody"},{"time":501000,"text":"who sees something wrong with whatever you have in mind."},{"time":504000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":507000,"text":"And it's very hard to find an ethicist who considers any change"},{"time":511000,"text":"worth making, because he says, what about the consequences?"},{"time":515000,"text":"And, of course, we're not responsible for the consequences"},{"time":518000,"text":"of what we're doing now, are we? Like all this complaint about clones."},{"time":524000,"text":"And yet two random people will mate and have this child,"},{"time":527000,"text":"and both of them have some pretty rotten genes,"},{"time":531000,"text":"and the child is likely to come out to be average."},{"time":535000,"text":"Which, by chimpanzee standards, is very good indeed."}]},{"cues":[{"time":541000,"text":"If we do have longevity, then we'll have to face the population growth"},{"time":544000,"text":"problem anyway. Because if people live 200 or 1,000 years,"},{"time":548000,"text":"then we can't let them have a child more than about once every 200 or 1,000 years."},{"time":554000,"text":"And so there won't be any workforce."},{"time":557000,"text":"And one of the things Laurie Garrett pointed out, and others have,"},{"time":561000,"text":"is that a society that doesn't have people"},{"time":566000,"text":"of working age is in real trouble. And things are going to get worse,"},{"time":569000,"text":"because there's nobody to educate the children or to feed the old."},{"time":575000,"text":"And when I'm talking about a long lifetime, of course,"},{"time":577000,"text":"I don't want somebody who's 200 years old to be like our image"},{"time":583000,"text":"of what a 200-year-old is -- which is dead, actually."}]},{"cues":[{"time":587000,"text":"You know, there's about 400 different parts of the brain"},{"time":589000,"text":"which seem to have different functions."},{"time":591000,"text":"Nobody knows how most of them work in detail,"},{"time":594000,"text":"but we do know that there're lots of different things in there."},{"time":598000,"text":"And they don't always work together. I like Freud's theory"},{"time":600000,"text":"that most of them are cancelling each other out."},{"time":604000,"text":"And so if you think of yourself as a sort of city"},{"time":608000,"text":"with a hundred resources, then, when you're afraid, for example,"},{"time":614000,"text":"you may discard your long-range goals, but you may think deeply"},{"time":618000,"text":"and focus on exactly how to achieve that particular goal."},{"time":622000,"text":"You throw everything else away. You become a monomaniac --"},{"time":625000,"text":"all you care about is not stepping out on that platform."},{"time":629000,"text":"And when you're hungry, food becomes more attractive, and so forth."},{"time":633000,"text":"So I see emotions as highly evolved subsets of your capability."},{"time":639000,"text":"Emotion is not something added to thought. An emotional state"},{"time":643000,"text":"is what you get when you remove 100 or 200"},{"time":647000,"text":"of your normally available resources."}]},{"cues":[{"time":650000,"text":"So thinking of emotions as the opposite of -- as something"},{"time":653000,"text":"less than thinking is immensely productive. And I hope,"},{"time":657000,"text":"in the next few years, to show that this will lead to smart machines."},{"time":661000,"text":"And I guess I better skip all the rest of this, which are some details"},{"time":664000,"text":"on how we might make those smart machines and --"},{"time":669000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":674000,"text":"-- and the main idea is in fact that the core of a really smart machine"},{"time":679000,"text":"is one that recognizes that a certain kind of problem is facing you."},{"time":684000,"text":"This is a problem of such and such a type,"},{"time":687000,"text":"and therefore there's a certain way or ways of thinking"},{"time":692000,"text":"that are good for that problem."},{"time":694000,"text":"So I think the future, main problem of psychology is to classify"},{"time":698000,"text":"types of predicaments, types of situations, types of obstacles"},{"time":702000,"text":"and also to classify available and possible ways to think and pair them up."},{"time":708000,"text":"So you see, it's almost like a Pavlovian --"},{"time":711000,"text":"we lost the first hundred years of psychology"},{"time":713000,"text":"by really trivial theories, where you say,"},{"time":716000,"text":"how do people learn how to react to a situation? What I'm saying is,"},{"time":722000,"text":"after we go through a lot of levels, including designing"},{"time":727000,"text":"a huge, messy system with thousands of ports,"},{"time":730000,"text":"we'll end up again with the central problem of psychology."},{"time":734000,"text":"Saying, not what are the situations,"},{"time":737000,"text":"but what are the kinds of problems"},{"time":739000,"text":"and what are the kinds of strategies, how do you learn them,"},{"time":742000,"text":"how do you connect them up, how does a really creative person"},{"time":745000,"text":"invent a new way of thinking out of the available resources and so forth."}]},{"cues":[{"time":750000,"text":"So, I think in the next 20 years,"},{"time":752000,"text":"if we can get rid of all of the traditional approaches to artificial intelligence,"},{"time":757000,"text":"like neural nets and genetic algorithms"},{"time":759000,"text":"and rule-based systems, and just turn our sights a little bit higher to say,"},{"time":765000,"text":"can we make a system that can use all those things"},{"time":767000,"text":"for the right kind of problem? Some problems are good for neural nets;"},{"time":771000,"text":"we know that others, neural nets are hopeless on them."},{"time":774000,"text":"Genetic algorithms are great for certain things;"},{"time":777000,"text":"I suspect I know what they're bad at, and I won't tell you."},{"time":781000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":782000,"text":"Thank you."},{"time":784000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}